## Clean Code Principles

- 🔴 **Avoid nested if statements** - Use guard clauses and early returns instead
- 🔴 **Limit parameters** - Functions should have 2 or fewer parameters; use object parameters for more
- 🔴 **Keep functions small** - Functions should be under 50 lines of code
- 🔴 **Single responsibility** - Each function should do only one thing and do it well
- 🔴 **Avoid cascading conditionals** - Replace if/else if/else if/else chains with switch statements or separate conditionals
- 🟠 **Use early return pattern** - Return early to reduce nesting and improve readability
- 🔴 **Use meaningful names** - Descriptive variable and function names that reveal intent
- 🔴 **Use verb-based function names** - Functions should be named with verbs that describe what they do
- 🟠 **Extract complex logic** - Refactor complex logic into smaller, well-named functions
- 🟡 **Maximum line length** - Keep lines under 80-100 characters
- 🟡 **Group related functionality** - Related code should be kept together
- 🟠 **Minimize comments** - Write self-documenting code; comments should explain "why" not "what"
- 🟡 **Consistent formatting** - Use consistent indentation, spacing, and brace style
- 🟠 **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)** - Eliminate duplicated code and logic
- 🟡 **YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It)** - Don't add functionality until it's necessary
- 🟡 **KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid)** - Keep code as simple as possible
- 🟠 **Fail fast** - Detect and report errors as soon as possible
- 🟠 **Prefer immutability** - Use const by default and avoid mutating state
- 🟡 **Law of Demeter** - Objects should only talk to their immediate neighbors
- 🟡 **Pure functions** - Functions should avoid side effects when possible
- 🟡 **Encapsulate conditionals** - Extract complex conditionals into well-named functions
- 🟡 **Replace primitives with types** - Use interfaces for domain concepts instead of primitives
- 🟡 **Tell, don't ask** - Tell objects what to do rather than asking for their state

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Early return pattern
function processUser(user: User | null): string {
  if (!user) return 'No user found';
  if (!user.isActive) return 'User is inactive';

  return `Welcome ${user.name}!`;
}

// ❌ BAD: Nested conditionals
function processUser(user: User | null): string {
  if (user) {
    if (user.isActive) {
      return `Welcome ${user.name}!`;
    } else {
      return 'User is inactive';
    }
  } else {
    return 'No user found';
  }
}
```

